TY  - JOUR
T1  - When Expectations Become Reality: Work-Family Image Management and Identity Adaptation
AU  - Ladge, Jamie J.
AU  - Little, Laura M.
Y1  - 2018/05/23
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2016.0438
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2016.0438
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 126
EP  - 149
VL  - 44
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Working parents often contend with how to effectively portray themselves as both devoted professionals and good parents. In this article we introduce the construct ?work-family image? as a cross-domain, collective image representing how competent an individual is perceived to be as a parent and a professional by key constituents in both work and life domains. We present a theoretical framework to explicate a process in which work-family image management drives work-family identity adaptation. Specifically, we suggest that work-family image management occurs when work-family norms, derived from societal, organizational, and familial expectations, create image discrepancies that drive impression management behavior. These behaviors, in turn, can create image-identity asymmetries and lead to work-family identity adaptation. We contribute to existing research by highlighting the dynamic interplay between image management and identity adaptation and explain the process by which work-family norms can influence working parents? identities.
AB  - Working parents often contend with how to effectively portray themselves as both devoted professionals and good parents. In this article we introduce the construct ?work-family image? as a cross-domain, collective image representing how competent an individual is perceived to be as a parent and a professional by key constituents in both work and life domains. We present a theoretical framework to explicate a process in which work-family image management drives work-family identity adaptation. Specifically, we suggest that work-family image management occurs when work-family norms, derived from societal, organizational, and familial expectations, create image discrepancies that drive impression management behavior. These behaviors, in turn, can create image-identity asymmetries and lead to work-family identity adaptation. We contribute to existing research by highlighting the dynamic interplay between image management and identity adaptation and explain the process by which work-family norms can influence working parents? identities.
